AB  - Mexico joined the Decade of Action for Road Safety 2011-2020 through the establishment of actions aimed at strengthening the five pillars proposed by the UN, which were embodied in the National Road Safety Strategy 2011-2020. From the middle of the Decade, it was observed that the global trends of reduction of deaths and severe injuries due to road accidents were not enough to meet the objectives of the Decade, making it necessary to implement more effective approaches and management systems to close the existing gap. Within the implementation of such approaches, various activities have been developed, ranging from specific initiatives to multi-institutional efforts. Specific initiatives include the implementation of new laws that regulate the minimum safety features that new vehicles and motorcycle helmets must meet, as well as the development of a Road Safety Audit Manual that will serve as a guide for the evaluation of the safety provided by the road infrastructure. Within the multi-institutional sphere, it is worth highlighting the efforts that have been made in the area of road safety management, implementing integration protocols and interinstitutional collaboration for the generation of the comprehensive database of road accidents, as well as the development of a system of indicators to track the evolution of road accidents and evaluate the effectiveness of countermeasures and programs. These efforts have had favorable results in the country's road safety, reporting in the last five years a decrease in the number of accidents; likewise, there is a decrease in the number of total victims resulting from road accidents, reporting less injured each year and stabilizing the number of deaths. This paper describes the previous aspects, as well as the main actions undertaken and the results obtained. Proposals are established for the strategy of the next decade, including awareness programs for all road users and integrate new concepts on human factor in the design of infrastructure, seeking to forgive human errors that may arise, among other important points such as the reduction of arrival times of pre-hospital medical attention and the adequate follow-up of the victims.
