AB  - When compared to all other types of crashes, wrong-way driving (WWD) crashes are much more likely to result in serious injuries and fatalities. Specifically, on divided highways, the risk of fatality is 20 to 25 times greater. In part, this appears to be due to limitations in the current “3Es of Traffic Safety” strategies (Engineering, Education, and Enforcement). This paper proposes an expanded “Safe System Approach” to address the role of all components of the traffic system that may lead to crashes. This paper identifies three main strategies: Access Management (AM), Traffic Safety Culture (TSC), and Intelligent Transportation Systems (ITS) / Connected Vehicle Systems (CVS). After describing each strategy, the paper focuses on AM and TSC. It is estimated that when the Safe System approach, as outlined in this paper, is universally applied, WWD crashes on divided highways will be significantly reduced.
