AB  - Conventional at-grade intersection designs present a significant challenge in the context of meeting the Safe System vision of preventing fatal and serious injuries. The combination of multiple conflict points and physical characteristics of some of these conflicts lead to high probability of sustaining fatal and serious injuries in at-grade intersection crashes. This paper outlines an analytical method for estimating risk of severe injuries at intersections. The method, X-KEMM-X, draws on previous published and new research by the authors on conflict point analysis, intersection geometry and the relationship between impact speed and severe injury probability. The method is used to assess the probability of a fatal or serious injury outcome in a crash at selected conventional at-grade intersection types. Then, a series of innovative Safe System-aligned intersection designs are evaluated using the same method. The paper compares these designs suggesting principles for Safe System intersection design guidance. The paper concludes with a discussion about the potential of X-KEMM-X method as a tool for quantitative Safe System evaluation of future road and intersection designs.
