AB  - Motorcyclists are among the most vulnerable road users. For motorcyclists in Victoria, Australia, the likelihood of serious injury or death in a crash is 34 times higher than for the occupants of a car. Although a combination of factors are generally at play in any crash, the engineering of the road surface and environment can have a significant impact on both the possibility of avoiding a crash and on the severity of injury to a motorcyclist should a crash occur. To address this issue, VicRoads commissioned a review of engineering design and maintenance standards, which then informed the development of a communications strategy - Making Roads Motorcycle Friendly. This paper provides the content, delivery and the evaluation of this world-first technical training package for road engineers, designers and operators. The paper then extends the communications strategy to deal with some of the key design issues involved in roads, roundabouts and motorcycles. Making Roads Motorcycle Friendly is a Victorian Motorcycle Advisory Council endorsed project, funded by the Transport Accident Commission Motorcycle Safety Levy and  delivered by VicRoads and Safe System Solutions Pty Ltd. It is a two hour seminar designed to raise awareness of the vulnerability of motorcyclists in terms of the road environment and highlight how road design/construction and maintenance/reinstatement works can be performed in ways that improve safety for motorcyclists. Over 800 Victorian engineers, road designers and maintenance staff have undertaken the training and an independent evaluation of the training package included an analysis of: 1) the post session evaluation forms (conducted immediately after each session);  2) the results of an electronic survey to participants; and 3) telephone interviews 5 to 15 months after seminars. The Victorian Making Roads Motorcycle Friendly resource and structure has now been used as the basis of the Western Australian, New South Wales and New Zealand versions of the training package. Following this overview of the communications strategy, the paper reports the results of an in-depth engineering investigation of some roundabouts in Victoria where motorcycle crashes have occurred and provides an illustrative example of design for motorcycle safety by examining roundabout design, maintenance and operation including turbo roundabouts.
