AB  - Since 2004, the Safe System approach has been adopted across Australia as a framework for road agencies to reduce the risk of death and serious injury on our roads. In many situations, applying the principles of the Safe System approach has acted to prevent crashes or reduce the severity of the resulting outcome. However, this is an ongoing process that will take time to embed across all areas of road infrastructure management. This paper looks at real-world crash incidents where serious injury has occurred, taking place prior to the adoption of the National Road Safety Strategy in 2011. The paper considers what the prime factors were surrounding each incident. Looking at advances brought down by the Safe System approach in the past five years, the paper then considers the likelihood that these advances could have prevented each crash, or mitigated its severity. This paper will serve to highlight how the Safe System philosophy functions in real world scenarios. It should be of value to practitioners when considering how to apply the Safe System principles to their road network.
